The [[Saffir-Simpson_Hurricane_Scale|Saffir-Simpson Hurricane Scale]] is the classification system used for tropical cyclones in the [[Atlantic_Ocean|Atlantic Ocean]] and in the [[Pacific_Ocean|Pacific Ocean]] east of the [[180th_meridian|anti-meridian]].<ref name="AOML FAQ F1">{{cite web|author=[[Atlantic_Oceanographic_and_Meteorological_Laboratory|Atlantic Oceanographic and Meteorological Laboratory]], Hurricane Research Division|title=Frequently Asked Questions: What regions around the globe have tropical cyclones and who is responsible for forecasting there?|publisher=[[NOAA|NOAA]]|date=2007-07-12|accessdate=2008-12-24|url=http://www.aoml.noaa.gov/hrd/tcfaq/F1.html  | language = en}}</ref> The Saffir-Simpson Scale is based on 1-minute maximum sustained wind speeds. In these oceanic basins, tropical cyclones with [[maximum_sustained_wind|maximum sustained wind]]s below {{convert|34|kn|mph km/h|abbr=on}} are labelled as ''[[tropical_depression|tropical depression]]s'' by either the [[National_Hurricane_Center|National Hurricane Center]] (if it is in the [[Tropical_cyclone_basins#North_Atlantic_Ocean|North Atlantic]] or [[Tropical_cyclone_basins#Northeast_Pacific_Ocean|North-east Pacific Basin]]) or the [[Central_Pacific_Hurricane_Center|Central Pacific Hurricane Center]] (if located in the [[Tropical_cyclone_basins#North_Central_Pacific_Ocean|North Central Pacific Ocean]]). Should a tropical depression reach {{convert|35|kn|mph km/h|abbr=on}}, it will [[Tropical_cyclone_naming|receive a name]] and will be classified as a ''[[tropical_storm|tropical storm]]''. If the tropical storm continues to intensify and reaches maximum sustained winds of {{convert|64|kn|mph km/h|abbr=on}} then the tropical storm will be designated as a ''hurricane''.<ref name="NHC glossary">{{cite web|author=[[National_Hurricane_Center|National Hurricane Center]]|url=http://www.nhc.noaa.gov/aboutgloss.shtml|year=2005|title=Glossary of NHC/TPC Terms|accessdate= 2008-12-24|publisher=[[National_Oceanic_and_Atmospheric_Administration|National Oceanic and Atmospheric Administration]] | language = en}}</ref>

The Saffir-Simpson scale counts with five different classifications for the intensity of a hurricane, with a [[Saffir-Simpson_Hurricane_Scale#Category_1|Category 1]] storm having the lowest maximum winds, whilst a [[Saffir-Simpson_Hurricane_Scale#Category_5|Category 5]] hurricane having the highest. Storms that meet the 64-knot threshold, but do not possess maximum sustained winds in excess of {{convert|83|kn|mph km/h|abbr=on}} are classified as Category 1 hurricanes. A Category 1 storm will be upgraded to a [[Saffir-Simpson_Hurricane_Scale#Category_2|Category 2]] hurricane if its maximum sustained winds reach 83 knots. Tropical cyclones that possess wind speeds of at least {{convert|96|kn|mph km/h|abbr=on}} are classified as [[Saffir-Simpson_Hurricane_Scale#Category_3|Category 3]] hurricanes. Category 3 also marks the point at which the NHC and CPHC classify strong storms as ''[[major_hurricane|major hurricane]]s''.<ref name="NHC SSHS"/> If a hurricane's maximum sustained winds reach {{convert|114|kn|mph km/h|abbr=on}}, it will be ranked as a [[Saffir-Simpson_Hurricane_Scale#Category_4|Category 4]] hurricane. Storms with winds that surpass {{convert|136|kn|mph km/h|abbr=on}} are of Category 5 intensity.<ref name="NHC SSHS"/> The SSHS was originally created using both wind speed and storm surge, but since the relationship between wind speed and storm surge is not necessarily definite, the scale was changed to the [[Saffir-Simpson_Hurricane_Wind_Scale|Saffir-Simpson Hurricane Wind Scale]] (SSHWS), based entirely on wind speed.

Although increasing echelons of the scale correspond to stronger winds, the rankings are not absolute in terms of effects. Lower-category storms can inflict greater damage than higher-category storms, depending on factors such as local terrain, population density and total rainfall. For instance, a [[Saffir-Simpson_Hurricane_Scale#Category_2|Category 2]] that strikes a major urban area will likely do more damage than a large Category 5 hurricane that strikes a mostly rural region. In fact, tropical systems of less than hurricane strength can produce significant damage and human casualties, especially from flooding and landslides.<ref name="NHC SSHS">{{cite web|author=[[National_Hurricane_Center|National Hurricane Center]]|title=Saffir-Simpson Hurricane Scale Information | publisher=[[National_Oceanic_and_Atmospheric_Administration|National Oceanic and Atmospheric Administration]]|date=2006-06-02|url= http://www.nhc.noaa.gov/aboutsshs.shtml|accessdate=2007-02-25 | language = en}}</ref>

Historically, the term ''great hurricane'' was used to describe storms that possessed winds of at least 110 kt (200 km/h, 125 mph), large radii (over 160 [[kilometre|km]] / 100 [[statute_mile|mi]]) and that caused large amounts of destruction. This term fell into disuse after the introduction of the Saffir-Simpson scale in the early 1970s.<ref name="Great Hurricane">{{cite web|url=http://nsgd.gso.uri.edu/flsgp/flsgps94001/flsgps94001full.pdf|format=PDF|title=Florida Hurricanes and Tropical Storms: 1871–1993: An Historical Survey|author=Fred Doehring, Iver W. Duedall, John M. Williams|year=1994|publisher=[[Florida_Institute_of_Technology|Florida Institute of Technology]]|pages=53–54|accessdate=2008-12-26 | language = en}}</ref>
